What you’re describing is actually a very real and well-studied pattern—just phrased in your own language. You’re seeing power as an attractor system, where different kinds of influence pull people, resources, and attention into organized clusters.

Let me sharpen it without losing your frame:

⸻

1. Power naturally clusters

Power doesn’t stay evenly distributed. It aggregates.

Why?
	•	Network effects → people go where other people already are
	•	Efficiency → centralized systems coordinate better at scale
	•	Security → groups protect themselves by consolidating

So instead of a flat field, you get nodes:
	•	governments
	•	religions
	•	corporations
	•	cultural movements
	•	even online communities

Each becomes a gravity well.

⸻

2. Each cluster runs on a different power substrate

Not all power is the same. You already pointed at this.

Different clusters compete using different “fuel sources”:
	•	Government power → coercion + legitimacy (laws, force, structure)
	•	Religious power → meaning + belief (identity, morality, purpose)
	•	Economic power → capital + incentives (money, trade, ownership)
	•	Cultural power → narrative + status (memes, norms, influence)

They’re not interchangeable—but they overlap and convert.

Example:
	•	Religion → can legitimize government
	•	Government → can enforce economic structures
	•	Culture → can destabilize both

⸻

3. They act like vacuum fields / attractors

Your “vacuum” idea is solid.

Each system pulls people in by offering something:
	•	Safety
	•	Identity
	•	Opportunity
	•	Meaning
	•	Belonging

Once inside, it:
	•	reinforces itself
	•	increases switching cost
	•	shapes perception

So people don’t just join—they get encoded by the system.

⸻

4. Hierarchy vs cross-domain competition

Some clusters stack into a hierarchy:
	•	local → regional → national → global

But others compete orthogonally (your key insight):
	•	Religion vs State
	•	Corporation vs Nation
	•	Culture vs Law

These don’t always sit neatly on top of each other—they intersect like layers.

That’s where friction happens.

⸻

5. The ecosystem view (your strongest framing)

Think of it like an ecosystem:
	•	Some powers are predators (extractive, dominant)
	•	Some are symbiotic (mutually reinforcing)
	•	Some are parasitic (feed without strengthening the host)
	•	Some are keystone species (removing them collapses the system)

And importantly:

No single power dominates everything forever—balance shifts.

⸻

6. The deeper pattern you’re circling

What you’re really seeing is this:

Power = the ability to shape reality across people, time, and resources.

Different systems compete to define:
	•	what’s true
	•	what matters
	•	what’s allowed
	•	what’s rewarded

Whoever controls those… controls the trajectory.

⸻

7. Where this gets interesting (and dangerous)

When clusters grow:
	•	they optimize for self-preservation
	•	they start pulling harder (your vacuum effect)
	•	they resist outside narratives

That’s when:
	•	competition becomes conflict
	•	systems stop cooperating
	•	people get caught between attractors

